"""
MKT Context Commentary — Hebrews chapters 12–13 (gap-fill pass)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-hebrews-12-13-gaps.py

Key decisions:
- ch12:1-4 athletic contest: Greco-Roman agōn metaphor; 4 Macc martyrs as athletes
- ch12:5-11 divine paideia: Stoic paideia theology (Seneca On Providence); Jewish wisdom tradition
- ch12:18-29 Sinai theophany phenomenology; Haggai 2:6 eschatological shaking
- ch13:2 philoxenia: Roman hospitium obligations; Didache regulations for itinerant teachers
- ch13:9 strange food teachings: Jewish dietary laws in mixed community context
- ch13:15 fruit of lips: Hosea 14:2 LXX; rabbinic transition from Temple to synagogue worship
- ch13:22 logos paraklēseōs: recognized synagogue homily genre (Acts 13:15)
- ch13:24 hoi apo tēs Italias: Roman hypothesis for destination; Clement of Rome's knowledge of Hebrews
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / "data" / "commentary" / source / f"{book}.json"
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / "data" / "commentary" / source / f"{book}.json"
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f"  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}")

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

HEBREWS = json.loads(r"""
{
  "12": {
    "2": "<p>\"Fixing our eyes on Jesus\" (<em>aphorōntes</em>) invokes the athletic practice of the runner fixing their gaze on the finish line rather than looking around at competitors or obstacles. The Stoic philosophy of attention (<em>prosochē</em>) taught that the disciplined mind must focus on the goal and not be distracted by irrelevant impressions (Marcus Aurelius, Meditations 4.3; Epictetus, Discourses 1.20). In Jewish martyrology (4 Maccabees 17:10-14), the martyrs are described as athletes who \"fixed their eyes\" on the prize of godliness throughout their torture. The specific phrase \"the joy set before him\" versus the \"shame\" of the cross invokes the Roman honor-shame calculus: the cross was <em>infamia</em> — the most dishonoring death, reserved for those society judged beneath the protection of honor. Jesus's despising of shame sets the community the example of how to navigate a culture that uses shame as a social weapon against the faithful.</p>",
    "3": "<p>\"Consider him who endured such opposition from sinners\" uses the Greek verb <em>analogizomai</em> — to reason by analogy, to calculate and compare — which was a standard philosophical exercise. The Stoics used the contemplation of exemplary figures (<em>paradoxoi</em>) as a moral exercise; Seneca recommends meditating on Socrates, Cato, and Laelius as exemplars of virtue (On the Tranquility of the Soul 3.3). Jewish martyr literature used the same technique: 4 Maccabees 16:16-23 exhorts the seven brothers to \"remember\" Abraham, Isaac, Jacob, Joseph, Phinehas, and Daniel as models. The specific focus on Christ's endurance of \"opposition from sinners\" against himself is the apostrophe most relevant to the community facing social opposition: they are directed to meditate on the one who endured this in its ultimate form.</p>",
    "4": "<p>\"You have not yet resisted to the point of shedding blood\" calibrates the community's suffering against the martyrdom standard. The Maccabean martyrs (2 Macc 6-7; 4 Macc 5-18) had set the paradigm of \"resistance to shedding blood\" — Eleazar and the seven brothers each resisted the tyrant's commands at the cost of their lives. The Martyrdom of Polycarp (2nd century, but reflecting earlier traditions) and the Acts of the Martyrs document the Christian continuation of this martyrology tradition. Hebrews' \"not yet\" is both pastoral encouragement (your suffering, though real, is not yet at the maximum) and warning (it may yet come to that). The community is positioned between the ordinary suffering they have experienced (10:32-34) and the blood-to-death standard of the faith-heroes they have just been asked to imitate.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The citation of Proverbs 3:11-12 (\"the Lord disciplines the one he loves\") places divine discipline in the context of the wisdom tradition's theology of parental formation. In the Jewish wisdom tradition, the father's rod was not punitive cruelty but educational necessity: Proverbs 13:24 (\"whoever spares the rod hates their children\"), 22:15 (\"folly is bound up in the heart of a child, but the rod of discipline will drive it far away\"), and 29:17 (\"discipline your children, and they will give you peace\") established a theology of formative discipline. Ben Sira 30:1-13 develops this at length, describing the properly disciplined son as one who brings joy to his father. The <em>paideia</em> (discipline, formation) vocabulary connected education, character formation, and physical correction in a single semantic field that was intelligible across both Greek and Jewish contexts.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The Roman institution of patria potestas (the father's legal authority over his children) made paternal discipline both a legal right and a social expectation. The paterfamilias held virtually unlimited power over his household; disciplining children through physical means was universally accepted and expected. The Mishnah tractate Avot reflects the Jewish expectation of structured intergenerational transmission: \"At five years old, the Torah; at ten, Mishnah... at thirteen, the commandments\" (Avot 5:21) — each stage accompanied by appropriate instruction and correction. The question \"For what children are not disciplined by their father?\" assumes the universal answer: none. An undisciplined child was regarded as either abandoned or rejected — the logic Hebrews will make explicit in v8.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The legal distinction between legitimate sons and <em>nothoi</em> (illegitimate children) had profound practical consequences in Greek and Roman law. The <em>nothos</em> in Athenian law could not inherit, could not be a citizen, and was excluded from religious and civic rites (Demosthenes, Against Stephanus 1.20). In Roman law, children born outside of recognized marriage were <em>spurii</em> or <em>vulgo quaesiti</em> — they had no claim on the paternal estate. The Mishnah (Kiddushin 3:12) also addresses the legal status of children born in prohibited circumstances. The argument is precise: if you are not disciplined, you are not in the father's legal family with inheritance rights — a social and legal reality the community would immediately understand.</p>",
    "9": "<p>\"The Father of spirits\" (<em>tō patri tōn pneumatōn</em>) is a divine title that appears in Numbers 27:16 (\"the God of the spirits of all flesh\") and in the Qumran thanksgiving hymns (1QH 4:25, 9:29: \"God of spirits\"). The title emphasized God's role as the creator and sustainer of the spirit-realm — all rational beings (humans and angels) owe their spiritual existence to God. In Greek philosophical theology, the cosmos was governed by a divine principle that stood in a paternal relationship to rational souls — Plato (Timaeus 37c-d) describes the Demiurge as the father of the cosmos's soul. The contrast between earthly fathers (who discipline partially and imperfectly) and the Father of spirits (who disciplines with perfect knowledge of the goal) is reinforced by the contrast between finite human wisdom and infinite divine wisdom.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The contrast between human discipline \"for a short time as they thought best\" and divine discipline \"for our good, that we may share his holiness\" reflects the distinction between short-term and long-term benefit that was central to Stoic philosophy. The Stoics distinguished between the <em>sumpheron</em> (beneficial, profitable) and the <em>hēdu</em> (pleasant, agreeable) — what is good for a person is not always what feels good. Epictetus (Discourses 1.28.5-6) argues that apparent evils are often genuine goods in disguise. Jewish Wisdom similarly distinguished: \"Whom God loves, he corrects\" (Prov 3:12); \"Before I was afflicted I went astray, but now I keep your word\" (Ps 119:67). The goal of sharing God's holiness (<em>hagiōtēs autou</em>) is the specific telos of divine discipline that human parental discipline can only approximate.</p>",
    "11": "<p>\"Peaceful fruit of righteousness\" (<em>karpon eirēnikon... dikaiosynēs</em>) uses the agricultural fruit-metaphor for character formation that was widespread in both Greek and Jewish ethics. Aristotle described virtue as the proper fruit of practical reason; the Stoics described virtue as the flower of the well-ordered soul. In Jewish wisdom (Prov 11:30: \"The fruit of righteousness is a tree of life\"; Amos 6:12; Isa 32:17: \"the effect of righteousness will be peace\"), the fruit-metaphor expressed the organic relationship between righteous living and its natural consequences. The Qumran Rule of the Community (1QS 4:7-8) describes the rewards of the Spirit of Truth as including peace, long life, and the fruit of eternal joy. Hebrews promises that the painful process of discipline produces this fruit — not immediately, but eventually, to those \"trained\" by it.</p>",
    "12": "<p>\"Strengthen your feeble arms and weak knees\" echoes Isaiah 35:3 (\"Strengthen the feeble hands, steady the knees that give way\") from the oracle of wilderness restoration. Isaiah 35 describes God's return to heal and restore his people — the blind see, the deaf hear, the lame leap, the mute sing — in the context of the eschatological return from exile. The physical metaphors of drooping hands and weak knees appear in Ezekiel 7:17 and 21:7 in the context of fear and devastation. In the athletic context Hebrews has established, these are the runner's symptoms of exhaustion: the arms lose their pumping power, the knees begin to buckle. The command to strengthen them is a pastoral exhortation to the spiritually exhausted to find renewed energy for the continuing race.</p>",
    "13": "<p>\"Make level paths for your feet, so that the lame may not be disabled, but rather healed\" draws on Proverbs 4:26 (LXX: \"make straight paths for your feet\") and the Isaiah 35 healing-oracle context. The concern for \"the lame\" within the community reflects the reality that groups under pressure contain members at different stages of spiritual vitality — some are running strongly, others are limping badly. The stronger members' responsibility is to clear the path for the weaker: if the race-track is strewn with obstacles, the limping runner will fall. The image combines athletic, medical, and road-construction metaphors in a single pastoral instruction: the health of the community's weakest members is the responsibility of its strongest.</p>",
    "14": "<p>\"Make every effort to live in peace with everyone and to be holy; without holiness no one will see the Lord\" connects two requirements: horizontal peace with all people and vertical holiness before God. Psalm 34:14 (\"Seek peace and pursue it\") and Matthew 5:9 (\"blessed are the peacemakers\") establish the peace-seeking imperative. The condition \"without holiness no one will see the Lord\" echoes Psalm 24:3-4: \"Who may ascend the mountain of the LORD? Who may stand in his holy place? The one who has clean hands and a pure heart.\" In Jewish temple theology, the vision of God was the ultimate goal of the priestly approach — only the pure could enter God's presence. The Beatitude (Matt 5:8: \"the pure in heart shall see God\") and the Mishnah's discussion of the high priest's preparation for the Yom Kippur approach to the divine presence both reflect the same theology of holiness-as-prerequisite-for-divine-encounter.</p>",
    "15": "<p>\"See that no one fails to obtain the grace of God and that no bitter root grows up to cause trouble and defile many\" adapts Deuteronomy 29:17-18 (LXX): \"lest there should be among you a man or woman whose heart turns away from the LORD our God... a root bearing poisonous and bitter fruit.\" The Deuteronomy context was the covenant renewal warning against secret idol-worship — the \"root of bitterness\" was the person whose heart had already defected while still appearing to be part of the covenant community. The community surveillance implied by <em>episkopountes</em> (overseeing, watching over) reflects the Qumran community's practice of communal moral accountability and the early church's mutual discipline procedures (Matt 18:15-17; Gal 6:1). The concern is not private sin but sin that \"defiles many\" — the communal contagion model of moral corruption.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Esau's classification as <em>bebēlos</em> (profane, irreligious) rather than simply morally weak reflects his covenant-violation character. In LXX usage, <em>bebēlos</em> describes that which is ritually common or profane, without respect for the sacred boundary. Esau's sale of his birthright (Gen 25:29-34) for bread and lentil stew was interpreted in Jewish tradition as a contemptuous rejection of covenant standing. The rabbis noted that Esau's request for food even before eating demonstrates his excessive appetite (b. Bava Batra 16b); the Targum on Genesis emphasizes Esau's denial of the resurrection and the world to come as the theological content of his profanity. The birthright was not merely a legal claim on a double inheritance share but the covenant position — the firstborn's special relationship with God and the family blessing. Exchanging this for immediate physical satisfaction was the paradigm of temporal versus eternal value-inversion.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Esau's inability to find \"a place of repentance\" (<em>metanoias topon</em>) despite seeking it \"with tears\" was interpreted in Jewish tradition as the irreversibility of certain covenant-violations. The rabbis discussed the limits of repentance — while repentance was always possible for the individual's relationship with God, certain social and legal consequences of sin were irreversible. The Genesis narrative (27:33-40) records Isaac's absolute inability to retract the blessing once given — it had transferred irrevocably to Jacob. Philo (On the Unchangeableness of God 50-69) argues that some divine decisions are as irrevocable as God's own nature. Hebrews uses this as a warning that the apostasy of ch. 6 and ch. 10 has an Esau-like character: there is a point at which the covenant-violation produces irreversible consequences regardless of subsequent tears.</p>",
    "19": "<p>\"The blast of a trumpet\" (<em>salpinggos ēchō</em>) and the \"voice of words\" at Sinai (Exod 19:16, 19) were the two characteristic auditory features of the Sinai theophany. The trumpet sound preceded and accompanied the divine voice at Sinai, and the sound was so overwhelming that Israel begged for it to stop (Exod 20:18-19). In Jewish liturgy, the shofar (ram's horn trumpet) sounded at Rosh Hashanah recalled the Sinai trumpet and also anticipated the eschatological trumpet of the resurrection (1 Thess 4:16; 1 Cor 15:52). Exodus Rabbah 29:9 develops the tradition that the divine voice at Sinai was divided into seventy tongues so all nations could hear it simultaneously. The Mishnah tractate Rosh Hashanah discusses the proper shofar blasts and their liturgical significance, embedding the Sinai trumpet in ongoing Jewish worship memory.</p>",
    "20": "<p>\"If even an animal touches the mountain, it must be stoned\" (Exod 19:12-13) illustrates the absolute holiness-barrier at Sinai. The gradated holiness of Sinai — the people must stay back, Moses can approach, only Moses goes all the way up — corresponded to the gradated holiness of the sanctuary: the outer courts accessible to laypeople, the inner courts to priests, the Most Holy Place only to the high priest once annually. The death penalty for even animal contact with the mountain extended the holiness-barrier to the natural world: no living creature, regardless of moral capacity, could enter the divine presence zone without authorization. This absolute sanctity-barrier was what made Sinai the paradigm of restricted access — and what makes the contrast with the open access of Mount Zion (v22) so theologically significant.</p>",
    "21": "<p>\"Moses said, 'I am trembling with fear'\" draws on Deuteronomy 9:19, where Moses describes his terror during the golden calf incident: \"I was afraid of the anger and wrath of the LORD.\" Hebrews applies this fear to the Sinai theophany itself — a combination of the Sinai context (Exod 19-20) with Moses's fear language from Deuteronomy 9. This composite citation was a recognized interpretive practice in Jewish biblical interpretation: different passages about the same event were combined to build a fuller picture. The specific inclusion of Moses's fear at Sinai had the rhetorical effect of showing that even the supreme mediator, the one who had unique face-to-face access to God, trembled at the theophanic encounter — making the contrast with the community's bold access to the heavenly Zion all the more striking.</p>",
    "23": "<p>\"The assembly of the firstborn, whose names are written in heaven\" combines two significant Jewish concepts. \"Firstborn\" (<em>prōtotokon</em>, plural) was a covenant-status term: Israel was called God's firstborn son (Exod 4:22), and the firstborn son held the privileged position in the family inheritance structure. The plural here extends the firstborn-status to all members of the heavenly assembly — they share the inheritance of the divine firstborn (Christ). \"Names written in heaven\" reflects the Book of Life traditions: Exodus 32:32-33 describes God's book of those who belong to him; Psalm 69:28 speaks of having one's name blotted from the book of the living; Daniel 12:1 promises deliverance for everyone found written in the book; and Revelation 3:5 and 20:12-15 develop the Book of Life extensively. The divine register of the covenant community was a concrete expression of divine covenant-loyalty.</p>",
    "24": "<p>\"The sprinkled blood that speaks a better word than the blood of Abel\" inverts the Genesis 4:10 imagery of Abel's blood crying out from the ground for vengeance. The blood of Abel cried for retributive justice — that cry was heard and Cain was cursed. The \"speaking\" of blood in the Jewish legal tradition reflected the idea that shed blood testified against its shedder (Num 35:33: \"blood pollutes the land\"; the Mishnah's dictum in Sanhedrin 4:5 about the blood of a murdered victim crying out to God). Christ's blood \"speaks better\" because it speaks forgiveness rather than vengeance — the same speaking-blood imagery but with the opposite content. This contrast uses the Jewish legal category of blood-testimony in an entirely new direction.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The warning not to refuse \"him who speaks\" draws on the Sinai precedent where Israel begged Moses to mediate rather than hearing God's voice directly (Exod 20:18-19; Deut 5:25-27). Israel's refusal of direct divine address at Sinai was not apostasy but creaturely recognition of their unworthiness to stand before the divine holiness. Hebrews uses this as the baseline for the warning: if even a God-fearing refusal of direct divine address (Sinai) brought consequences, refusing the heavenly voice of grace carries incomparably greater consequences. The phrase \"did not escape when they refused him who warned them on earth\" establishes the historical precedent; \"how much less shall we if we turn away from him who warns from heaven\" applies the <em>kal va-chomer</em> logic.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The Haggai 2:6 citation — \"Once more I will shake not only the earth but also the heavens\" — comes from the post-exilic prophet's oracle during the rebuilding of the Second Temple (520 BCE). Haggai was urging the returned exiles to prioritize the Temple's completion; the promised shaking was God's guarantee that the nations' wealth would fill the rebuilt Temple (Hag 2:7-9). Hebrews reads this eschatological shaking not as a past event (the return from exile) or a future geopolitical event (conquest of nations) but as the removal of the entire created order in preparation for the unshakeable kingdom. Jewish apocalyptic similarly expanded the Haggai shaking into a cosmic event: 1 Enoch 1:6-7 describes the mountains shaking and the high hills sinking in the final judgment; 4 Ezra 9:3 uses earthquake imagery for the eschatological transition.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The theological argument that the shaking removes \"created things\" to reveal \"what cannot be shaken\" reflects the Jewish theology of the eternal versus the temporal. The rabbinic tradition distinguished between <em>olam ha-zeh</em> (this world, with all its mutability) and <em>olam ha-ba</em> (the world to come, permanent and divine). The Dead Sea Scrolls (1QH 11:25-26) contrast the fragility of human existence with the firmness of divine foundations. The Stoic concept of <em>ekpyrōsis</em> (cosmic conflagration that renews the world) provided a Hellenistic parallel — the present world-order as temporary and subject to dissolution. Hebrews synthesizes these traditions: the Jewish eschatological framework (two ages) with the specific claim that the community has already received the unshakeable kingdom through Christ.</p>",
    "29": "<p>\"For our God is a consuming fire\" (citing Deut 4:24 and 9:3) brings the Sinai-Zion contrast to its conclusion. The divine consuming fire had multiple referents in Jewish theology: the pillar of fire at the Exodus (Exod 13:21-22; 14:24), the fire at Sinai (Exod 19:18; 24:17; Deut 4:12), the fire of divine judgment on Israel's enemies (Isa 10:17; 29:6; 30:30), and the fire of divine holiness that consumed unauthorized offerings (Lev 10:2 — Nadab and Abihu) and the rebellious (Num 16:35 — Korah's followers). The same consuming fire that destroys the wicked is the consuming fire of God's own holy nature. For the community approaching the heavenly throne with confidence (4:16; 10:19-22), the concluding reminder that this God is a consuming fire reinforces the reverence-within-confidence that marks the new covenant's paradoxical access.</p>"
  },
  "13": {
    "1": "<p>\"Let brotherly love continue\" (<em>hē philadelphia menetō</em>) names the community's bond with the word for sibling affection. <em>Philadelphia</em> (love of brothers and sisters) was used in both literal family contexts and extended metaphorically to close community bonds. Roman moral writers praised sibling loyalty as a natural virtue; Plutarch devoted an essay to it (<em>On Brotherly Love</em>). In Jewish communities, the covenant people were regularly addressed as brothers and sisters (Deut 15:7; Neh 5:1), and the obligations of brotherhood included financial support, ransom from captivity, and legal advocacy. In early Christianity, the household terminology (brothers, sisters, mothers, fathers) was applied to the entire community — a countercultural extension of family obligations beyond biological kinship. The call for it to \"continue\" (<em>menetō</em> — remain, abide) acknowledges that it already exists but needs to be maintained against the pressures that were causing community fragmentation.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The obligation to remember prisoners and the mistreated \"as if you were their fellow prisoners\" appeals to the empathy mechanism of imaginative solidarity. Roman imprisonment was brutal: prisoners were chained in dark, cold cells, often with no provision for food or water — survival depended on friends and family bringing supplies (Lucian, Toxaris 17-18; the papyri preserve letters requesting food and clothing for imprisoned relatives). Christian prisoners faced the additional burden of being imprisoned for their faith, which might cause family members to distance themselves to avoid implication. Paul's letters from prison (Phil 1:13-14; Col 4:3; Philemon) document both his imprisonment situation and the community's role in supporting him. The Acts of the Martyrs routinely record the Christian community's visits to their imprisoned members.</p>",
    "4": "<p>\"Let marriage be held in honor by all\" addresses a community context in which sexual asceticism may have been present alongside sexual license. The early Christian movement contained both tendencies: some groups (the proto-gnostic teachers Paul warns against in 1 Tim 4:3) forbade marriage as spiritually inferior; others (in the Corinthian community, 1 Cor 6:12-20) treated bodily actions as spiritually neutral. Roman sexual culture was characterized by a double standard — men's extramarital relations with slaves and prostitutes were socially accepted while women's were severely punished. The Jewish purity tradition insisted on the sanctity of the marital relationship and the prohibition of all sexual relations outside it (Lev 18; 20). Hebrews' single verse addresses both distortions: the marriage bed must be both honored (against ascetic disparagement) and pure (against license).</p>",
    "6": "<p>The citation of Psalm 118:6 (\"The Lord is my helper; I will not be afraid; what can anyone do to me?\") places the community's financial security within the tradition of the Hallel psalms. Psalm 118 was sung at the major Jewish festivals (Passover, Pentecost, Tabernacles, Dedication) and in the Temple liturgy on festival days. The Mishnah (Pesahim 10:5-7) describes its recitation at the Passover Seder. By citing Ps 118:6 as the community's response to the divine promise of non-abandonment, Hebrews draws on one of the most liturgically prominent texts in Jewish worship. The question \"what can anyone do to me?\" was the rhetorical challenge that God's presence made to all human power — an implicit comfort for a community that had experienced property confiscation and social pressure.</p>",
    "7": "<p>\"Remember your leaders, who spoke the word of God to you. Consider the outcome of their way of life, and imitate their faith\" describes the practice of commemorating and imitating community founders and martyred leaders. The specific phrase \"consider the outcome\" (<em>anatheoroyntes tēn ekbasin</em>) — where <em>ekbasis</em> means the exit, the end, the way out — suggests that these leaders had died, possibly as martyrs. The practice of commemorating martyred leaders was central to early Christian community identity: the letters of Ignatius of Antioch (early 2nd century), the Martyrdom of Polycarp, and later hagiographic texts all show communities organized around the memory and example of their martyred founders. The instruction to imitate their faith parallels the faith-catalogue of ch. 11 — the faith-heroes are both the ancestors and the most recent community leaders.</p>",
    "9": "<p>\"Strange teachings\" about food (<em>brōmasin</em>) that are \"of no benefit to those who observe them\" almost certainly refers to the Jewish dietary laws and perhaps the ongoing debates about whether Jewish Christians needed to observe them. The Jerusalem Council's compromise (Acts 15:19-20) had addressed Gentile Christian food practices; Paul's letters deal extensively with food disputes in mixed communities (Rom 14:1-23; 1 Cor 8; Col 2:16-23). In the specific context of Hebrews' argument, the food-related teachings that are \"of no benefit\" are likely connected to the Levitical purity system — which Hebrews has argued is superseded by Christ's priesthood. \"The heart should be strengthened by grace, not by food\" inverts the Jewish purity logic: ritual food-observance regulated the boundary of covenant standing, but Hebrews locates covenant standing in grace, not food-observance.</p>",
    "10": "<p>\"We have an altar from which those who minister at the tabernacle have no right to eat\" establishes the Christian community's exclusive claim to a sacrificial system that the Levitical ministers cannot share. In the Jewish sacrificial system, portions of most offerings were eaten by the priests: the showbread, portions of the grain offerings, the breast and right thigh of peace offerings. Leviticus 7:1-36 specifies the priestly portions with precision. The act of eating the sacrifice was part of the covenantal meal that enacted participation in the offering (1 Cor 10:18: \"do not those who eat the sacrifices participate in the altar?\"). Hebrews' claim that the community has an altar is therefore a claim to a complete sacrificial system — including the priestly privilege of eating from the sacrifice, which those who maintain the tabernacle service cannot access.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The Levitical regulation that the sin-offering animals burned outside the camp (Lev 16:27; Lev 4:11-12, 21) created the typological connection that Hebrews is developing. The distinction was precise: the burnt offering was entirely consumed on the altar; the peace offering's portions were shared between God, priest, and worshipper; but the sin-offering whose blood was brought into the sanctuary had its carcass removed and burned entirely outside the camp. This complete removal outside the sacred space was the sin-offering's characteristic: it absorbed the pollution of sin and was therefore itself treated as polluted — it could not remain in the holy camp. The typological application to Christ is the inversion: he went outside not because he was polluted but to bring purification to those who would come to him there.</p>",
    "12": "<p>\"Jesus also suffered outside the city gate to make the people holy through his own blood\" provides the historical-geographic anchor for the typological argument. The crucifixion at Golgotha (\"the place of the skull\") occurred outside the walls of Jerusalem — John 19:20 notes that \"the place where Jesus was crucified was near the city,\" and John 19:41 that \"at the place where Jesus was crucified, there was a garden.\" Skull Hill/Golgotha was outside the Jerusalem city walls, in the liminal zone between the city's sacred space and the impure world beyond. The theological significance of this geography was recognized in early Christian interpretation: the place of execution outside the city was simultaneously the place of pollution and the place of purification — the outside-the-camp sin-offering transformed into the Golgotha sacrifice.</p>",
    "14": "<p>\"Here we do not have an enduring city, but we are looking for the city that is to come\" articulates the pilgrim theology that runs through ch. 11-13. The city (<em>polis</em>) was the fundamental unit of Greco-Roman civilization — citizenship in a polis defined one's legal identity, political participation, and social belonging. Paul's claim to Roman citizenship (Acts 22:25-29) and the Philippians' pride in their Roman colonial citizenship (Phil 1:27; 3:20) show how important civic identity was. Jerusalem itself — the holy city that stood at the center of Jewish identity — was either still standing (if Hebrews is pre-70 CE) or had just fallen (if post-70 CE). In either case, the claim that \"we have no enduring city here\" is a radical devaluation of the earthly city — whether Rome or Jerusalem — in favor of the heavenly city (12:22) toward which the community moves as pilgrims.</p>",
    "15": "<p>\"A sacrifice of praise — the fruit of lips that confess his name\" adapts Hosea 14:2 LXX: \"take with you words and return to the LORD your God; say to him: 'Forgive all sins and receive us graciously, that we may offer the fruit of our lips.'\" Hosea's oracle, spoken at a time when the northern kingdom could no longer offer the Levitical sacrifices because of its exile, proposed verbal confession and repentance as the sacrifice that words could provide when animals could not. The early rabbinic tradition (after the Temple's destruction in 70 CE) developed this Hosean principle into the theology of <em>avodah she-ba-lev</em> (service of the heart — prayer as the equivalent of sacrifice): the Mishnah and Talmud record the transition from Temple sacrifice to synagogue prayer as the primary form of divine service. Hebrews anticipates this transition by grounding it not in the Temple's absence but in its fulfillment in Christ.</p>",
    "16": "<p>\"Do good and share\" (<em>eupoiia kai koinōnia</em>) as sacrifices acceptable to God reflects the prophetic tradition that located true worship in ethical action rather than ritual performance. Micah 6:6-8 (\"what does the LORD require of you but to do justice and love kindness and walk humbly with your God\"), Isaiah 58:6-7 (loosing the unjust bonds, sharing bread with the hungry), and Amos 5:23-24 (\"away with the noise of your songs... but let justice roll down like waters\") all established the prophetic principle that God values justice and compassion over cultic activity. James 1:27 (\"religion that God our Father accepts... is this: to look after orphans and widows in their distress\") reflects the same principle in early Christian ethics. Hebrews frames these practical acts of community solidarity as the new covenant's authentic worship — the sacrifice God now accepts.</p>",
    "18": "<p>\"We are sure that we have a clear conscience\" (<em>kalēn syneidēsin echomen</em>) is an apologetic statement within what appears to be a situation of suspicion or accusation. In the Greco-Roman world, the <em>syneidēsis</em> (conscience, literally co-knowledge with oneself) was the inner moral tribunal that a person of integrity could invoke as witness to their conduct. Cicero (On Duties 3.44) and Seneca (Letters 43.5) both describe the conscience as the internal judge that cannot be deceived. The author's claim to a clear conscience and the desire to \"live honorably\" (<em>kalōs anastrophēnai</em>) suggests the community or its leadership faced accusations of improper conduct — perhaps related to their departure from synagogue affiliation, their support of imprisoned members, or some aspect of their community life that outsiders criticized.</p>",
    "19": "<p>\"I particularly urge you to pray so that I may be restored to you soon\" reveals a personal situational dimension of the letter. The language of \"restoration\" (<em>apokatastathō</em> — to be fully returned, reinstated) may indicate that the author is imprisoned, traveling, or otherwise separated from the community by circumstances beyond ordinary travel. Paul uses similar language in Philemon 22 (\"I hope to be restored to you in answer to your prayers\") from prison. The request for community prayer on behalf of the author's travel-plans places the letter's exhortations in a concrete relationship: the author is not a distant theoretician but a pastor who wants to return to his community and continues their relationship through prayer and correspondence.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The benediction \"the God of peace\" (<em>ho theos tēs eirēnēs</em>) was a divine title used throughout Jewish and early Christian liturgical contexts (Rom 15:33; 16:20; Phil 4:9; 1 Thess 5:23). In the Jewish liturgy, the <em>Shalom</em> blessing concluded multiple prayers: the Kaddish, the Amidah, the Birkat Kohanim (priestly blessing of Num 6:26). The mention of \"the blood of the eternal covenant\" draws the entire argument of chapters 7-10 into the benediction: the peace God gives is grounded in the covenant secured by the blood of the eternal priest-sacrifice. The description of Jesus as \"the great shepherd of the sheep\" (cf. Ps 23; Ezek 34:23-24: \"I will place over them one shepherd, my servant David\") invokes both the Davidic-pastoral and the Ezekiel-messianic shepherd traditions, positioning the benediction within the full scope of the OT's messianic hope.</p>",
    "21": "<p>\"Equip you with everything good for doing his will\" (<em>katartisai hymas en panti agathō</em>) uses the <em>katartizō</em> verb that appears in Ephesians 4:12 for the \"equipping of the saints\" for ministry, and in the Gospel accounts of mending fishing nets (Matt 4:21). The word carries the sense of fitting something out completely for its purpose — the community is fitted for will-doing as a ship is fitted out for a voyage. The phrase \"may he work in us what is pleasing to him, through Jesus Christ\" reflects the theological conviction shared with Paul (Phil 2:13: \"it is God who works in you to will and to act according to his good purpose\") that the community's own will-doing is itself a divine act within them. The benediction closes the entire letter's argument by attributing both the community's obedience and its acceptance to the God who simultaneously commands and enables.</p>",
    "22": "<p>\"Bear with my word of exhortation\" (<em>tou logou tēs paraklēseōs</em>) provides the letter's own generic self-identification: a <em>logos tēs paraklēseōs</em> (a word of encouragement or exhortation). This phrase appears elsewhere in Acts 13:15, where the synagogue ruler in Pisidian Antioch invites Paul and Barnabas: \"Brothers, if you have a word of exhortation for the people, please speak.\" The <em>logos paraklēseōs</em> was a recognized genre of synagogue homily — a sermon that encouraged, exhorted, and applied Scripture to the community's situation. Hebrews' own self-identification as this genre positions it within the tradition of Jewish-Christian synagogue preaching rather than purely epistolary form — it is a sermon that has been written down and sent, not merely a letter with theological content.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The mention of \"our brother Timothy\" who has been released is one of the few personal details in the letter, connecting it to the Pauline circle. Timothy is mentioned in multiple Pauline letters (1-2 Timothy, Phil 1:1, Col 1:1, Philemon 1, 1-2 Thess) as Paul's closest traveling companion and representative. If this is the same Timothy (and the Greek suggests familiarity — \"our Timothy\" — that would connect the author and recipients to the same apostolic network), his release from some form of custody is significant. Acts 16:3 introduced Timothy; the Pastoral Letters show him in leadership roles in Ephesus and elsewhere. The mention of his release and the conditional plan for a joint visit (\"if he arrives soon, I will come with him\") grounds the theological treatise in the practical realities of first-century Christian travel and community networks.</p>",
    "24": "<p>\"Those from Italy send you their greetings\" (<em>hoi apo tēs Italias</em>) is one of the letter's key hints about either authorship or destination. The phrase can be read two ways: (a) the author and Italian Christians are writing from Italy to a community elsewhere — \"those from Italy\" being Italian Christians currently with the author; or (b) Italian expatriates living where the letter was written are sending greetings back to their home community. If reading (b), the letter is destined for Rome or another Italian community. The Roman hypothesis for the letter's destination is supported by Clement of Rome's apparent knowledge of Hebrews (1 Clement, c. 96 CE, appears to cite Hebrews several times), suggesting it was known in Rome very early. The salutation reflects the normal closing practice of Pauline letters (Rom 16:21-23; Phil 4:21-22; Col 4:10-14).</p>",
    "25": "<p>\"Grace be with you all\" (<em>hē charis meta pantōn hymōn</em>) is the minimal Pauline benediction form. Paul's letters typically close with some form of this grace-benediction (Rom 16:20; 1 Cor 16:23; 2 Cor 13:14; Gal 6:18; Phil 4:23; Col 4:18; 1 Thess 5:28; 2 Thess 3:18). The brevity of Hebrews' closing benediction (compared to 2 Cor 13:14's full trinitarian form) matches the simpler forms of the shorter letters. The word <em>charis</em> (grace) as the closing word gathers up the letter's entire theological argument: the community has access to God, endurance in trial, and the community obligations of ch. 13 — all ultimately grounded in the grace of the God who made the eternal covenant in Christ's blood and who equips the community for every good work (v21).</p>"
  }
}
""")

def main():
    existing = load_comm("mkt-context", "hebrews")
    merge_comm(existing, HEBREWS)
    save_comm("mkt-context", "hebrews", existing)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    print(f"Hebrews 12-13 mkt-context gaps filled: {len(existing)} chapters, {total} verses written.")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()
